  "notes": "The same roster told twice (2 Sam 23 / 1 Chr 11). The three, Abishai, and Benaiah align verse-for-verse; 'the thirty' is a flat list where each verse names one or two men, so the edges carry the name (or the shared exploit) and cross between verses — that is what the labels are for. Gaps left on purpose: Eleazar's sword-weary hand (2 Sam 23:10), Elika the Harodite, the scholarly-disputed tail (Eliphal/Eliphelet, the 'son of Nathan' pair, Paarai/Naarai), and the sixteen extra warriors the Chronicler appends (1 Chr 11:42-47). The chief's name and number even disagree — Jashobeam against three hundred, the Tachmonite (Adino the Eznite) against eight hundred — so that edge is labelled by office, not name.",
  "created": "2026-06-14T00:00:00Z",
